{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012UHn5mnWaXKCc3AFFVB7ah","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/17-2-lane-pool.md`.\n\n**Summary:** Created story 17-2-lane-pool with 12 acceptance criteria, 6 task groups, dev notes with architecture constraints, implementation patterns (Promise.race loop, event emission, epic independence check), edge cases, and boundary definitions. All ACs tagged `test-provable` since the lane pool is a pure scheduling module testable via mocked dependencies (WorktreeManager, executeFn callback) without running the app or a full environment.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:** None.\n\n**Workarounds applied:** None.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- AC #5 (epic independence by ordering) is a simplified heuristic. The architecture doc mentions a post-MVP explicit DAG approach. The current ordering rule (\"epic N waits for all epics < N\") may be overly conservative for unrelated epics, but matches the spec.\n- The `Promise.race` identity problem (knowing *which* promise resolved) requires wrapping each lane promise in a `.then()` that tags the result with `epicId`. This is a known pattern but easy to get wrong — documented in edge cases.\n\n**Observations:**\n- Story 17-1 is marked `backlog` in sprint-status.yaml but has a completed story file and was committed (`c5385bf`). The sprint-status.yaml appears stale/not updated after 17-1 was implemented.\n- All 12 ACs are `test-provable` — the lane pool is entirely unit-testable with mocked WorktreeManager and a fake execute callback. No runtime or environment dependencies.\n\n## Token Report\n\n- Total tool calls: 14\n- By tool: Read: 6, Glob: 6, Grep: 2, Bash: 1, Write: 1\n- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): `ls implementation-artifacts` (~5 lines, truncated by head)\n- Files read: 6 unique, 6 total reads (no file read 3+ times)\n- Redundant operations: Glob for `story*` patterns tried 3 slightly different patterns to find existing story files — could have been one broader glob. Minor inefficiency."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ad48764fa71393f68 (use SendMessage with to: 'ad48764fa71393f68' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 54145\ntool_uses: 25\nduration_ms: 166795</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5f276c07-4ea2-4b01-86c9-d8e4e30ebe94","uuid":"e6fbfd17-d122-4221-b351-c0fa48e7971b","timestamp":"2026-04-03T20:04:48.911Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /bmad-create-story for story 17-2-lane-pool. The sprint-status.yaml is at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/sprint-status.yaml. Auto-discover the next backlog story and create it. For each AC, append a verification tier tag using this decision tree:\n\n**Tier Decision Tree (append one `<!-- verification: {tier} -->` tag per AC):**\n- `test-provable` — AC can be verified by building the project and running tests/linters/grep. No running app needed. Examples: 'function X exists', 'type Y is exported', 'test Z passes', 'file has <300 lines'.\n- `runtime-provable` — AC requires running the app locally and checking its behavior (CLI output, HTTP response, process lifecycle). No Docker stack needed. Examples: 'CLI prints usage when invoked with --help', 'server responds 200 on /health', 'process exits 0 on valid input'.\n- `environment-provable` — AC requires a full environment (Docker stack, database, observability, multi-service interaction). Examples: 'logs appear in VictoriaLogs', 'metrics are emitted to VictoriaMetrics', 'container communicates with service X'.\n- `escalate` — AC genuinely cannot be automated (requires physical hardware, paid external service, human visual judgment). This is rare. Examples: 'UI looks correct on mobile', 'payment processes successfully in production'.\n\nDefault to `test-provable` when unsure. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Problems encountered (errors, ambiguities in epic definition, missing context)\n- Workarounds applied (anything you did that felt hacky or suboptimal)\n- Risks identified (ACs that seem untestable, unclear requirements, missing dependencies)\n- Observations (anything surprising or noteworthy about this story)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`\n\nMANDATORY — Also end your response with a `## Token Report` section:\n- Total tool calls: N\n- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, other: N\n- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): command (~N lines each)\n- Files read: N unique, M total reads (list any file read 3+ times)\n- Redundant operations: describe any repeated reads, duplicate commands, or wasted calls","agentId":"ad48764fa71393f68","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story file created at `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/17-2-lane-pool.md`.\n\n**Summary:** Created story 17-2-lane-pool with 12 acceptance criteria, 6 task groups, dev notes with architecture constraints, implementation patterns (Promise.race loop, event emission, epic independence check), edge cases, and boundary definitions. All ACs tagged `test-provable` since the lane pool is a pure scheduling module testable via mocked dependencies (WorktreeManager, executeFn callback) without running the app or a full environment.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Problems encountered:** None.\n\n**Workarounds applied:** None.\n\n**Risks identified:**\n- AC #5 (epic independence by ordering) is a simplified heuristic. The architecture doc mentions a post-MVP explicit DAG approach. The current ordering rule (\"epic N waits for all epics < N\") may be overly conservative for unrelated epics, but matches the spec.\n- The `Promise.race` identity problem (knowing *which* promise resolved) requires wrapping each lane promise in a `.then()` that tags the result with `epicId`. This is a known pattern but easy to get wrong — documented in edge cases.\n\n**Observations:**\n- Story 17-1 is marked `backlog` in sprint-status.yaml but has a completed story file and was committed (`c5385bf`). The sprint-status.yaml appears stale/not updated after 17-1 was implemented.\n- All 12 ACs are `test-provable` — the lane pool is entirely unit-testable with mocked WorktreeManager and a fake execute callback. No runtime or environment dependencies.\n\n## Token Report\n\n- Total tool calls: 14\n- By tool: Read: 6, Glob: 6, Grep: 2, Bash: 1, Write: 1\n- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): `ls implementation-artifacts` (~5 lines, truncated by head)\n- Files read: 6 unique, 6 total reads (no file read 3+ times)\n- Redundant operations: Glob for `story*` patterns tried 3 slightly different patterns to find existing story files — could have been one broader glob. Minor inefficiency."}],"totalDurationMs":166795,"totalTokens":54145,"totalToolUseCount":25,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4351,"cache_read_input_tokens":49260,"output_tokens":533,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4351},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
