{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01J5dz8FwhQ5vQhY4hrEgpDq","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Story 17-2 is complete. All tasks implemented, all tests pass, no regressions.\n\n**Summary:**\n- Created `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/lane-pool.ts` — the lane pool module with all types (`EpicDescriptor`, `LaneStatus`, `Lane`, `LaneEvent`, `PoolResult`, `EpicResult`, `ExecuteEpicFn`, `LanePoolError`) and the `LanePool` class implementing `Promise.race` scheduling, event emission, epic independence checks, and edge case handling.\n- Created `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/__tests__/lane-pool.test.ts` — 24 unit tests covering all 12 acceptance criteria.\n- Updated `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/17-2-lane-pool.md` — all tasks/subtasks marked `[x]`, status set to `review`.\n\n**Test results:** 4837 tests pass across 179 files (24 new, 4813 existing). Zero regressions. Build compiles cleanly.\n\n## Session Issues\n\n- **Epic independence semantics (AC #5):** The independence check (`isEpicReady`) prevents epic N from starting if any epic with index < N is still active. This means with `maxParallel=2`, only the first batch of epics runs concurrently — subsequent epics must wait for ALL preceding epics to complete before starting. This is a batch-style parallelism, not a sliding-window. The fill loop collects candidates before adding to activeLanes to allow the initial batch to start together. This matches the spec's reference code but may feel surprising — the user might expect epic 3 to start as soon as epic 1 finishes (while epic 2 is still running), but it won't.\n- **No workarounds applied.** All patterns followed from story Dev Notes and existing codebase conventions.\n- **No TODOs left behind.**\n- **Catch block lint rule:** The project enforces `// IGNORE:` comments on empty catch blocks. Added the required annotation.\n\n## Toke